Tasks

  1. Note you need to be careful when reading in the data - have a look at the file before you read it in and figure out how to read it without manually changing the file.
df <- read_csv("S1Dataset.csv")
## Rows: 207 Columns: 26
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (19): Group, Methion., SAM, SAH, 8-OHG, Adenosine, Homocysteine, Cystein...
## dbl  (7): SAM/SAH, % DNA methylation, fGSH/GSSG, tGSH/GSSG, fCystine/fCystei...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
clean_df <- df |>
  mutate(across(everything(), ~ suppressWarnings(as.numeric(.x)))) |>
  mutate(Group = df$Group)
features <- c("SAM/SAH","% DNA methylation","fGSH/GSSG","tGSH/GSSG",
"fCystine/fCysteine","% oxidized", "Vineland ABC")
train_df <- df %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.character), ~na_if(.x, ""))) |> 
  mutate(across(!Group, as.numeric)) |>           
  filter(Group %in% c("ASD","NEU")) |>
  mutate(Group = factor(Group)) |>                         
  select(Group, any_of(features))
## Warning: There were 18 warnings in `mutate()`.
## The first warning was:
##  In argument: `across(!Group, as.numeric)`.
## Caused by warning:
## ! NAs introduced by coercion
##  Run `dplyr::last_dplyr_warnings()` to see the 17 remaining warnings.
  1. Use rpart() to grow a tree that distinguishes the ASD and NEU groups, and give the confusion matrix and the proportion of people (from these two groups) correctly classified. Plot the tree (showing labels make sure you set the margin in the plot call to make room for the labels).
fit1 <- rpart(Group ~ ., data=train_df, method="class")
pred1 <- predict(fit1, type="class")
results1 <- tibble(True = train_df$Group, Pred = pred1)
conf1 <- table(results1)
conf1
##      Pred
## True  ASD NEU
##   ASD  80   3
##   NEU   9  67
mean(results1$True == results1$Pred)
## [1] 0.9245283
results1 |>
  group_by(True) |>
  summarise(acc = mean(True==Pred))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   True    acc
##   <fct> <dbl>
## 1 ASD   0.964
## 2 NEU   0.882
rpart.plot(fit1, main="Default tree")

  1. The dataset makes the classifier look good, because the number of ASD and neurotypical participants are equal. In reality, ASD affects about 1.5% of people. Run rpart() with the prior argument (see the help page), to build a tree based on population prior probabilities of 0.015 and 0.985. Report the confusion matrix and the proportion of ASD and NEU groups correctly classified. Plot the tree.
fit2 <- rpart(Group ~ ., data=train_df, method="class",
parms=list(prior=c(0.015, 0.985)))
pred2 <- predict(fit2, type="class")
results2 <- tibble(True = train_df$Group, Pred = pred2)
table(results2)
##      Pred
## True  ASD NEU
##   ASD  66  17
##   NEU   0  76
mean(results2$True == results2$Pred)
## [1] 0.8930818
results2 |>
  group_by(True) |>
  summarise(acc = mean(True==Pred))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   True    acc
##   <fct> <dbl>
## 1 ASD   0.795
## 2 NEU   1
rpart.plot(fit2, main="Tree with population priors")

  1. Suppose that false negative classifications (missing ASD) are thought to be more important than false positive (suspecting ASD). Run rpart() with the prior argument as in the previous question and also with the loss argument saying that false negatives are 10 times as bad as false positives. Report the confusion matrix and the proportion of ASD and NEU groups correctly classified. Plot the tree. Did you get the result you expected?
lossmat <- matrix(c(0,10, 1,0), nrow=2)
fit3a <- rpart(Group ~ ., data=train_df, method="class",
parms=list(prior=c(0.015,0.985), loss=lossmat))
pred3a <- predict(fit3a, type="class")
results3a <- tibble(True = train_df$Group, Pred = pred3a)
table(results3a)
##      Pred
## True  ASD NEU
##   ASD  66  17
##   NEU   0  76
mean(results3a$True == results3a$Pred)
## [1] 0.8930818
results3a |>
  group_by(True) |>
  summarise(acc = mean(True==Pred))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   True    acc
##   <fct> <dbl>
## 1 ASD   0.795
## 2 NEU   1
rpart.plot(fit3a, main="Tree with priors + 10x FN cost")

Both ASD and NEU were correctly classified.

Now do the same except set the penalty for false negatives to 100 times.

lossmat100 <- matrix(c(0,100, 1,0), nrow=2)
fit3b <- rpart(Group ~ ., data=train_df, method="class",
parms=list(prior=c(0.015,0.985), loss=lossmat100))
pred3b <- predict(fit3b, type="class")
results3b <- tibble(True = train_df$Group, Pred = pred3b)
table(results3b)
##      Pred
## True  ASD NEU
##   ASD  66  17
##   NEU   0  76
mean(results3b$True == results3b$Pred)
## [1] 0.8930818
results3b %>% group_by(True) %>% summarise(acc = mean(True==Pred))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   True    acc
##   <fct> <dbl>
## 1 ASD   0.795
## 2 NEU   1
rpart.plot(fit3b, main="Tree with priors + 100x FN cost")

With this ASD was classified well but some NEU were not.

  1. Use this final tree to predict for the SIB group (all of whom are actually neurotypical). What proportion are correctly classified?
sib_df <- clean_df |>
  filter(Group=="SIB") |>
  select(all_of(features))
pred_sib <- predict(fit3b, newdata=sib_df, type="class")
mean(pred_sib=="NEU")
## [1] 0.8085106

About 80.85% were correctly classified as NEU to be the final tree.
